<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 10:1<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If65ee7b16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I6059a720933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Remand</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94f9de1ce1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:1.</label.designator><headtext>Role of remand under the statute</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The statute creating the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation contemplates transfer of actions by the Panel for consolidated or coordinated pretrial proceedings and then remand of all transferred actions to the districts in which they were filed for trial.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If65ee7b26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] In practice, remand occurs much less frequently. <eos/><bos/>Nonetheless, it is important to understand the Panel&apos;s remand procedures for they may ultimately be used in every case before the Panel.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If65ee7b16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If65ee7b26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914131" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I6fa48c706b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407(a)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The statute is reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:19" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If65f0ec06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:19</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 10:1<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
